description.text:
A 3-D rendering of a hyperboloid of one sheet ("basket" surface), part of my "Gallery of Quadric Surfaces." The design starts in Sage, export to X3D (resulting file included), then import X3D into Blender. In Blender, edit to remove artifacts Sage leaves behind, like a cube of lines around the figure, then "thicken" the surface so that Cura can recognize it as a solid object:

  1. select Properties -> Modifiers (wrench icon) -> Add Modifier -> Solidify
  2. set Thickness to 0.1 and click Apply

Now export to STL, then import STL into Cura. In Cura, scale (because graph units in Sage become millimeters in Cura) and situate figure on print platform, then export STL again to form the STL thing file here.

Here is the Sage code to generate the figure:

u,v=var('u,v')
parametric_plot3d([sqrt(1+v^2)*cos(u), sqrt(1+v^2)*sin(u), v], (u,0,2*pi), (v,-3,3), aspect_ratio=1)

Since Sage is Python-based, be sure to check line breaks. Note that the surface is defined parametrically and plotted using the parametric_plot3d() method.

description.text:
This is a highly customizable replacement toilet paper roll holder. It is a one piece print that has the spring mechanism built-in as the outer exoskeleton. The recommended material that I remixed the spring idea from recommends using ABS. However, I did my prints in both PLA and CPE with no issues with flexibility. If the result seems to stiff, try increasing the rings variable or decreasing the pillars variable.

I lost the original holder from my apartment (don't ask how one loses such a thing). I bought a replacement from my local hardware store down the block, but the diameter of the pegs were too large to fit. I could have measured mine and looked on Amazon. But I figured that over-engineering a solution to 3D-print was a much better Idea

Variables that you can control:
roll_width: width of the outer part of roll; the radius
ring_width: how wide each ring is going to be
ring_height: the thickness of each ring, 1mm is a pretty good value for me
actual_roll_length; This may vary depending on your holder, but 132mm is a good length for mine
inner_clearance: how much space between the inner beam and the exoskeleton, I used 2mm, but even tighter might work. Too loose will make the roll bendy side to side (maybe not desirable)
rings: How many rings to create. 10-20 is a good range. More rings should make it more flexible, because there's a larger area to distribute the flexing.
pillars: How many pillars per layer. 3 or 4 is a pretty good number for a roll width that is around the same size as the toilet paper inner cardboard. You may need to use 2 or 3 if your making it skinnier
cap_height: how high to make each cap
peg_width: radius of the peg. For sure measure this, mine was 4mm, but not all hardware is the same
peg_length = how high to make each peg, measure your own hole, mine was 3mm
pillar_thickness: thickness of pillars, make this thicker for strength, I've always used 2mm

description.text:
My Girlfriend's bike shop sold us a replacement throttle for her moped for like 30 dollars (for this tiny little part)....except it was a partially broken part when we got it and no returns allowed. It happened to be in better shape than the one that broke off her bike, and was enough for me to remake it and slightly over-engineer it. You may need to put either some foam rubber where the part meets the handlebar, or use liquid electrical tape before tightening it down to keep it from sliding on the bar (PLA doesn't deform well so its sized to the bike exactly, may be able to make a slightly undersized version to torque down without adjustment if using ABS.

Feel free to make more versions of this, I'd really love to see people be able to stick it to manufacturers overpriced replacement parts or even print almost every part on a bike. I just don't want others profiting off my work without cutting me in. Things like this should be free or printed at cost, and could be if the world wasn't run by the greedy.

A little liquid electrical tape on the place where it connects to the actual metal handlebar is useful. Can't remember what size nut and bolt to hold it together, just bring to home depot/lowes...they always seem to have em. (common size)

title: Nintendo Switch credit card size cartridge / game cart holder

description.text:
Someone asked me to design something similar to a product they had seen that holds 4 SD cards and can fit in a wallet.

The dimensions for that product were slightly larger than a credit card and about 5 mm thick. I made this one slightly smaller that a credit card (length and width wize) to compensate for its height when going into a leather sleeve. I had to create this design with a 6mm height in order to make sure there's a 1mm wall on top and bottom of the cartridges as the game carts themselves are 4mm thick.

DISCLAIMER: THIS IS UNTESTED and I'm not sure how it will print....I do not own a printer so I'm just posting it here for the person who requested it. I THINK that maybe printing it standing up right (long ways up) with some rafts might minimize the ammount of support material in the upper two slots when it's standing up. However, I'm not sure how much support material will be inside the lower two slots and how easy it would be to file it out.

title: Legends of Andor game box organizer, includes expansion
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is my first attempt at creating a game box organizer. I created this in 123D Design and I have included that file here, in case you need to make some edits (like separating some pieces to make them smaller for some printers). The largest piece is 221mm. Everything else is 200mm or smaller.

This organizer securely holds all pieces, instructions, and boards for the main game, Legends of Andor, by Ole Steiness, as well as the New Heroes expansion. All parts use 2mm wall thickness for a good, sturdy feel and to allow removal from the box for setting up on your game table. All game pieces are well covered to prevent spillage between games, and everything fits without removing the printed box insert (see included pictures). All parts have at least one bottom edge with a fillet, to aid in removing from the print bed. And, where possible, I also added a fillet to keep the sharp plastic edges away from the game box seams. The entire assembly fills the full dimension of the box, which helps preserve the box when stacking smaller games above or below this one.

title: Printrbot Play Hot End Fan Shroud
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
For as long as I've owned my printrbot, I've searched high and low for an effective fan shroud that would get better airflow around the hot end. Many solutions have been presented, but every single one required removing the metal hotend cover. I still prefer the look and style of the metal cover that printrbot designed, so I finally made my own design that could work with it. The only caveat is that the fan has to be on the exterior of the fan shroud.

This part is not compatible with my Printrbot Play light. I actually created my own version of the RGB lights that Printrbot put on the new simple. Not sure I'm going to post the mount for it because they require custom PCBs.

Supports:

No

Notes:

The square end of the shroud should sit on the build plate. The STL file isn't saved in the right orientation.

Assembly
  1. Remove the metal shroud from your printrbot.
  2. Remove the upper fan from your printrbot.
  3. Carefully unclip the cable from the edge of the fan. The cable should now only be attached by the solder joints in the center of the fan. This allows the fan to fit flush on the front of the shroud without showing the cable.
  4. Reinsert the fan cable through the hole from the front.
  5. Preinstall one of the plastite screws onto the printed part to help line it up.
  6. Place the printed part on the inside of the shroud, making sure that the cable fits through one of the notches in the part.
  7. Screw in both plastite screws.

When installing the metal shroud, be sure that the cables from the hotend don't get caught in the fan shroud.

Also included is a noctua_plug.stl which are meant to be seated in the two far holes of the fan which aren't used for mounting (need to print two). I believe they help leaking air.

title: Noctua Fan mod long version: MP Mini Select 3D PLA & PETG 40mm Fan Shroud

description.text:
Remix of my Noctua Fan mod: MP Mini Select 3D PLA & PETG 40mm Fan Shroud (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2250288) which is a remix of MP Mini Select 3D PLA & PETG 40mm Fan Shroud (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1676718) that can be used for the Noctua Fan.
I believe the original design is great for 40mm fans especially the 1cm thick versions as they don't have as much pressure and there is less backdraft with this design as the air is basically going down.

Modification of original design:
1) the shroud nozzle has been extended by 3.5mm to hopefully point more air onto the print.
2) larger holes so one can use the anti-vibration mounts (brown mount in photo). Still only two holes are available.
3) improved the notch where the fan clips attach. No supports needed.

The shroud needs to be properly aligned as it is just barely higher than the nozzle. There is a little more blow back, but I think it is made up by more air on the print. I'll let you the user decide.
Warning!: Because clearance is so tight, if unintentional artifacts are too high on a print job, the shroud may hit them. Example stringers from initialization, or initial layers being bumpy.

Just as with my original remix (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2250288):
Also included is a noctua_plug.stl which are meant to be seated in the two far holes of the fan which aren't used for mounting (need to print two). I believe they help leaking air.

Extra are noctua_screw_nut.stl, which are a skew/nut that can be used instead of the anti-vibration mounts (need to print two). Especially useful if try to switch to different shrouds. It does make the fan sit lower than the mounts so be careful as the back end of the fan may try and go up.

To reduce air leakage can use masking tape around the seam.

title: E3Dv6 fan duct for dc42 IR height sensor V1

description.text:
A combination E3Dv6 fan duct and dc42 IR height sensor mount, compatible with either E3D's original, or new style heater block + silicone sock.

Primary design goal:
Absolute minimal z-axis and rotational movement relative to the E3Dv6 Heatsink, by inherent firm rotational and vertical clamping pressure.

Improvement potential:
For greater peace of mind, a method to mechanically secure the duct to an E3Dv6 heatsink in rotation could be incorporated, possibly by way of a locking grub-screw or other clamp arrangement.

This part is freely available for further derivation directly in Onshape - links are available in the section 'How I Designed This', below.

Feedback here or in Onshape is much appreciated.

Printer:

Wiener90

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.5mm nozzle, 0.3mm layer height, x1 (0.42mm) perimeter

Infill:

35%

Notes:
  • Designed to be printed with the duct inlet face flat to the print bed.
  • I found that when printed at 50mm/s (compared to 30mm/s) the internal corner geometry is created 'slightly mis-formed' and this noticeably improves the part's grip on an E3Dv6 Heatsink - especially rotational grip. Z-position grip on the Heatsink appears to be equally good independent of print speed. This isn't ideal from a design perspective, but there you go - it is V1. Please leave any print-experience feedback in the comments and I'll consider tweaking the geometry.

• Zero or very minimal cleanup was the goal. Please post any contrary experience in the comments.
  • All the holes have small chamfers to offset the tendency of the fixing screws pulling material out of the holes.
  • To prevent a gap forming between fan and duct during assembly (due to the E3D supplied fan mounting screw threads also positively engaging with the fan mounting hole internal walls) it is best to rest the duct with its exit side flat on a bench while screwing the fan to the duct and applying positive pressure to both through the screwdriver.
  • The Sensor PCB can be mounted on either side of the tabs; I've yet to gain any experience to suggest a more favourable side of the tabs. Currently I have mine mounted on the inside of the tabs, to place it as close as possible to the nozzle. Electrical-short protection is provided by Kapton tape applied over the rear of the PCB prior to assembly and additionally by the E3D silicon sock over the heater block. Furthermore on my printer - any significant rotation that might cause a short is prevented by the proximity of the duct and fan to the X-axis bearings.

Designed in Onshape - post processed in MoI3D

Currently, Onshape doesn't have the capability to create the variable radius fillets visible along each of the four curved external edges of this part. To create those, the part V0 was exported as an STP file and the variable radius fillet details were added using MoI3D. Finally, the dumb solid was re-uploaded to Onshape as part V1.

The closest workaround to the variable radius fillet problem I came up with is the part B1 - for reference only.

To attach the dc42 IR height sensor (v1.1) on my latest RepRap printer, I started out using a Mini differential IR / E3D V6 stock fan mount - by maczero. I like the simplicity of that mount, but unfortunately it created and uncovered more issues than it solved:

  • the stock E3D supplied 30mm heatsink fan was made a little noisier than without the mount fitted - possibly due to it affecting the fan inlet flow,
  • it moved the height sensor far enough away (laterally) from the extruder nozzle that the dc42 supplied 3-pin power and signal connector collided with my printer's RH Z-shaft; a DC42 Mini height sensor board support for e3d v6 - by simon0362 may have addressed that issue by placing the sensor PCB closer to the hotend, however both mounts were ultimately affected by the third issue:
  • the original E3D-v6 Fan Duct - by joshuarowley42 didn't grip the Heatsink firmly enough to prevent Z-movement of anything hung off it - primarily due to the requirement for a draft angle on the walls of injection moulded parts.

The Fan duct and Mini Differential IR sensor v1.1 mount for E3Dv6 hot end on Kossel - by dc42 wasn't an option either, due to the physical constraints of my X-carriage and extruder.

I brought myself an Alienware 13 R3 gaming laptop for when I am away on work and want to play my games. One thing I noticed was when playing the machine would (unsurprisingly) get hot. Running a full GTX1060 means lots of heat that needs venting.

With the machine sat on a firm surface it sits only a few millimeters from it, this means the air is somewhat constricted (although it looks like there are side vents on the machine as well to draw additional air in).

I have made these simple feet to boost the back end up and make it easier for the laptop to breath. It also means when I use it in my living room, where it has to sit on the floor, it is able to suck up air without being 'filtered' through the carpet.

One final thing is that it adjusts the angle of the keyboard and has, for me anyway, made typing a slightly more comfortable affair.

-UPDATE-
I have added a second, two part, version. This has a plastic section, and where the grip touches the laptop on top and the feet, a section that I printed using FPE. This give more grip on the laptop and more friction on the feet to stop it moving on harder surfaces. This needs to be dual extrusion printed as the feet are secured inside the clip to ensure they don't get pulled off if the laptop is moved about on them.

-UPDATE 2-
A support bar has been included as well. This helps spread the load when using the laptop on a softer surface (a deeper pile carpet or bed) and tries to keep the back lifted to air can still reach the fan inputs.

During Lifetime, my K8400 started to collect more and more burned Filemant, which turned
black and sometimes touched with the print, which was not so nice at all.
So i decided to create my own Kapton Guard around the hotend, as Filament very hardly sticks on Kapton but can be removed from there quite well.

Ingredients

  • a Piece of Kapton Tape(I have pleanty as it also goes to the heatbed)
  • Sheet of Baking Paper
  • Super Glue
  • Paper printer

Instructions

Use Super Glue on the edges of an A4 Paper and stick it to the Baking Paper. Let it firm during you put something heavy onto it. Then cut off the excessive baking paper off the A4 sheet, so you can insert it into the printer.
Print the provided PDF File onto the Baking paper now. Be careful, the Toner does not hold very well there.
There are Right- and Left- Handed Hotends, so make sure that you select the proper template, but appearantly there are enough trials.
Then Stick the piece of kapton Tape onto the Template and cut it out with a pair of scissors. The Hole for the Nozzle can best be cut with a Stanley Cutter, but it needs to be sharp. Then Carefully remove the Kapton Tape from the Baking paper. Make sure that it does not break.
In order to attach the Kapton Tape to the Hotend, I really recommend to unmount it from the printer. Maybe we want to clean it from the burnt plastic, too, also remove the small M3x8 Skrew for the moment.
Then carefully stick the Kapton to the Hotend starting with the Bottom layer. You can easily use the Nozzle and the dotted lines as adjustment.
This is it. Then carefully assemble the nozzle again. Should be better print experience from now on.

description.text:
This is a case to hold a digital volt meter which also provides a USB charging outlet. The electronic components can be found here

I wanted an easy way to monitor my charging system status on my motorcycle, since I have several "power hungry" accessories installed (most notably a heated jacket and grips). This digital volt-meter provides a solution while at the same time providing a low-amp (500 milliamps) charging port. The thing is a case to hold the device securely and provide an easy mounting solution.

The bottom holds the electronics securely without the need for screws, although two of the stand-offs have pilot holes designed into them. The top has good interference fit on my printer, so no glue or other fastener is necessary to hold the two parts together. The wires are shrouded from moisture, but I would definitely not consider the solution waterproof. It's mounted in a well-protected area under my dashboard, and I haven't had a problem with moisture to date.

Monoprice MakerSelect (v1)

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.28 Layer

Infill:

100%

Notes:

Depending on how well your printer handles overhangs, you may need to print with supports. The wire shroud on the top part is at a 45-degree angle, so it should print okay without supports on a well-dialed-in printer.

Assembly

Fit the circuit board into the bottom piece and verify it fits securely. Use mounting screws to secure if necessary (it may be necessary to drill the standoffs to accommodate mounting screws). Connect the wires to the left side of the circuit board before snapping the top piece in place so that you don't run into issues with the shroud.

I use Scotch Extreme fasteners to hold the case to the motorcycle. After verifying fit, attach both parts of the fastener strip to the under-side of the mounting tab on the case. Peel the adhesive from the strip and put the case in place. Press firmly and then let it sit a while to allow the adhesive to cure.

• Print one clip using the "1 dodecahedron disk test clip.stl" file. Place both slots of the clip onto disks to make sure the hole is of appropriate size to allow the clip to grab the disk without slipping off. The disk doesn't have to go all the way into the end of the slot - the clip just has to be able to firmly grab the disk without slipping. If the slots seem too big or too small, you can scale the .stl file up or down, and then apply the same scaling to the "30 dodecahedron disk clips.stl" file.
    • (You can take a chance and skip step 1 and go straight to step 2. I printed the clips on a MakerBot Replicator 2 with 2 shells, 10% infill and a raft. Oddly one of the slots for each clip ended up a bit wider than the other slot even though the slots are the same width in the .stl file, but the clips still worked fine.)

  • Print 30 clips using the "30 dodecahedron disk clips.stl" file.

  • You can optionally print the dodecahedron clip placement template PDF to help properly position the clips on the disks.

  • Assemble the disks one at a time until you have a dodecahedron.

  • You can optionally glue or tape the clips in place once you are done with assembly.

description.text:
A major disadvantage of buying knitting wool from dope-headed hippies is the fact that it doesn't come in ready to use form. It has to be pre-washed, color-fixated and -last but not least- wound up onto spools or into the familiar playthings of the common household cat.
In order to save my son from being used as a living wool-holder by his knitting-crazy mother, I designed this thing.
Design was by myself, although I frankensteined parts from other things into it:

http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1832235
From this one I used the rollers as a mount for the skateboard bearings.

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1959208
Here I used screw and screw hole of the back plate for the table mount.

Design principle is a scissor-extender on two movable mounting plates. Two, because I was too lazy to design a fix for one of them. Some fixation for the mounting plates is provided by the friction between the bearings and the aluminium rod. Important ! The aluminium rod has to be of the anodized (matte) type to fit into the holes of the bearings and provide the necessary friction !
The whole device is to be mounted on the edge of a table w/ a max thickness of 30mm (less if you want to use a rubber protector on the mount). The rod will extend horizontally from the table. However, I found this to be a bit clumsy/unstable, so I will design a vertical mount later on.

On printing: 50% is probably too much for most of the parts. However, the table mount NEEDS AT LEAST 50%. 70% is better. Ah, and use PETG for the table mount because PLA is not flexible enough.

BoM (printed):
2 Mounting Plates
Rod protector knob
Table mount
Screw
Mounting bracket
8 scissor parts w/ thick end
Thin scissor parts (count depends on desired extension)

BoM (other):
2 608 Skateboard Bearings
8mm anodized aluminium rod
M3x10 screws (lots of 'em)
M3 Nylock nuts (again: lots of 'em)
M3 screws (I think it was 16 or 18mm), new version uses 20mm
M3 Nuts

UPDATE !
I changed the design for the table mount from a horizontal rod position to a vertical one. Just choose the variant you desire.

Hint:
The plastic screw has a really tight fit. Scaling the width and height (NOT the length) of this to 99% improves usability a lot.

title: Samsung TV accidental button push prevention

description.text:
This is a little contraption that makes it much harder to accidentally push the extremely sensitive power button on a particular model of Samsung TV (the UE46C6700). We use one of these in the office as an oversized computer monitor during scrum sessions, and people kept on bumping against the power button while using the mouse. This print makes it much less likely that the button will be accidentally touched, an accurate finger poke is required to turn off the TV.

I had printed a first prototype of this in flexible PLA, but it triggered the button when touching any part of the print. I modified the model to be more open and printed it in ABS instead, and this print does not have that problem. I'm not sure whether the shape of the model caused the problem, or the flexible PLA is actually conductive at the high-frequency electromagnetic field that is used by the touch buttons, but this second model does the job perfectly.

title: goPro Hero 2 Diving Lense under water flat lense no blur
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Hi,

this is an flat lense for an GoPro Hero 2 watertight housing. The Glas lense and the plastic Ring form the original housing will be removed and instead you can fit the new mounting plate (which you have to print) to your housing. The original rubber gasket will be under the new mounting plate. The original screws will clamp the new plate down. (but thats for later). You have to find and O-Ring which the inner diameter of 34-35mm and the outer diameter of 38-39. I found one in my toolbox. Now you need a "Plexiglas" plate with about 4mm thinkness. I turned mine in a lathe but you can also do it by hand (diameter 60mm). Clamp the new mounting Plate and the Plexiglas plate togehter and drill very slowly and without minimal pressure and some WD40 as lubricant the 6 holes. After that you need 6 M3 nuts (stainless stell) and 6 Bolts with 10mm long M3 thread (stainless stell).

Mounting:

  1. Clean all Surfaces
  2. Fit the original Rubber Gasket on the Housing
  3. Get you new 3D printed Mounting plate
  4. Get yourself a sodering iron and head up the M3 Nuts, place one on the top of your soldering iron and push the Nut into the Nut spaces in the back of the Mouting Plate. (be carefull)
  5. Get your O-Ring and lubricate it with some silicon spray
  6. Place the O-Ring into the groove of the new mounting plate
  7. Get your Plexiglas plate and put it on top of the O-Ring
  8. Get the Screws and push them into the drilled holes
  9. Screw the Plexiglas plate togehter with the new mouting plate (carefully and with a cross pattern - like Car Wheels)

Maybe you need to trim the new mounting plate a little bit on one side where the knop for the record button from he thousing is but thats not a big problem.

I tested mine, it works fine - but i have not tested it to the extrems - no scuba diving so far.
Test it without the camera in the housing if its sealed

So be carefull and have fun, but no garantee ;)

description.text:
My lever broke off. It wouldn't push the rolling wheel to the motor, didn't feed filament so couldn't print anymore. Luckily I had an old spare one. Since that one was the wrong color, I decided to print a new one. But to avoid the same part breaking at the same place, I made some (very small) enhancements to make it a bit stronger.

Basis of this version was the original 3.1-024_lever.stl. Using SketchUp I removed all triangle lines from the flat surfaces to make it easier to change. Then I added my additional lines to widen the part at the place it broke.

Notes:

No support was needed. One brand of PLA filament was a bit droopy, but some filing was enough to clean the part.

Changing original STL files using SketchUp

I don't have the original design source files, but it's fairly simple to import the STL files and modify them. Using SketchUp I first removed all triangle lines from the flat surfaces to make the part easier to modify. Then I added some ruler lines and drew additional lines to create the new surfaces needed to widen the part at the place it broke. Finally I cleaned the drawing up by deleting old lines from the surfaces and by navigating into the internals of the part to remove all internal surfaces that were no longer needed.
